@rileybrownai: From a pure “Granola-style product” perspective, Riley’s app looks slightly better overall.  It delivers a smoother end‑to‑end flow: record → high‑quality transcription → clear AI summary, plus an intuitive meeting detail screen where transcript and summary are easy to view together.  His calendar integration (upcoming events list + tap‑to‑record) also works reliably enough for the challenge, and folders are baked into the user experience early on.
Vishal’s Swift app is more impressive from a native iOS engineering and architecture standpoint, with solid use of EventKit, AVAudioRecorder, Apple’s speech framework, and a nicer recording animation.  But in the constraints of “5 prompts, no manual coding,” he runs into issues: API errors on AI summaries and folder functionality that doesn’t fully work, even though the calendar integration itself is very strong.
So if the goal is “which clone feels closer to a usable Granola‑like app in just five prompts,” Riley’s VibeCode build wins by a narrow margin.  If the question is “whose stack sets you up better for long‑term, production‑grade native iOS development,” then Vishal’s Claude Code + Swift approach has the edge.

 @shangobashi  ​ First, for clarification (since there still isn't an exact definition) when I say "vibe coders" I mean non-technical people using AI tools to generate code. I don't mean experienced devs using AI tools.

That said, when it comes to the whole limitations thing I didn't forget and I don't care. He knows nothing about software and someone like this will not survive in this industry if they don't grow (and I suspect most "vibe coders" will not). 

To have a channel this large based all around AI and AI dev tools but also have to ask what the freaking CD command does is funny as hell. Hell I'd say it shows he's a better salesman than a dev tbh lol. It's like someone illiterate teaching other illiterate people how to write novels with AI and using visual/audio tools to get it done but having no idea what the quality of the novel actually is lol.
